{"has_more_entries": true, "subscriptions": "", "error": "", "posts": [{"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "text", "uuid": "1ASZf6zwDE", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 59, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "", "id": 8593314, "raw_content": "I MEAN IT SEEMS LIKE IT SHOULD BE OBVIOUS AND ALREADY DONE, NO?\n\nThink of this like the CULTURAL equivalent of Tariff's!!!\n\n_____\n\n\nI propose a new law: any country that does not uphold free speech at a level comparable to the United States should face restrictions when it comes to accessing U.S.-based internet companies, platforms, and digital infrastructure. Right now, governments that censor speech, limit dissent, and tightly control information are still able to participate fully in open systems that are built on freedom of expression. That contradiction weakens the meaning of those values.\n\nIf a country limits what its own people can say, read, or share, but still benefits from open communication tools abroad, it creates an uneven situation. Closed systems are taking advantage of open ones without offering the same in return. That is not a balanced exchange.\n\nSetting limits would make the standard clear. Access to open platforms should come with a basic respect for free expression. Countries that consistently show hostility toward those principles through censorship and state control should not have unrestricted access to systems built on those freedoms.\n\n**This is not about shutting the world out. It is about making sure the values behind these platforms actually matter in practice, not just in theory.**\n", "author": "HeNotMedicated", "created": 1777649133992, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "HiimHillaryClinton", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "I PROPOSE A NEW LAW: Countries Without Full Free Speech Should Be Blocked From U.S. Internet Platforms", "last_comment_created": 1777653151636, "content": "<p>I MEAN IT SEEMS LIKE IT SHOULD BE OBVIOUS AND ALREADY DONE, NO?</p>\n<p>Think of this like the CULTURAL equivalent of Tariff's!!!</p>\n<hr />\n<p>I propose a new law: any country that does not uphold free speech at a level comparable to the United States should face restrictions when it comes to accessing U.S.-based internet companies, platforms, and digital infrastructure. Right now, governments that censor speech, limit dissent, and tightly control information are still able to participate fully in open systems that are built on freedom of expression. That contradiction weakens the meaning of those values.</p>\n<p>If a country limits what its own people can say, read, or share, but still benefits from open communication tools abroad, it creates an uneven situation. Closed systems are taking advantage of open ones without offering the same in return. That is not a balanced exchange.</p>\n<p>Setting limits would make the standard clear. Access to open platforms should come with a basic respect for free expression. Countries that consistently show hostility toward those principles through censorship and state control should not have unrestricted access to systems built on those freedoms.</p>\n<p><strong>This is not about shutting the world out. It is about making sure the values behind these platforms actually matter in practice, not just in theory.</strong></p>\n", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 7, "score_up": 59, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet